<paragraph blockId="18.[213,340,1179,1202]" box="[213,340,1179,1202]" pageId="18" pageNumber="885">
<emphasis box="[213,340,1179,1202]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="885">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[213,1170,1218,1688]" pageId="18" pageNumber="885">
For details of external features, epidermis, musculature, nervous system and alimentary system, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" box="[396,622,1250,1274]" pageId="18" pageNumber="885" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[213,1170,1218,1688]" pageId="18" pageNumber="885">
Testes as described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" box="[528,768,1282,1306]" pageId="18" pageNumber="885" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
, discharge into sperm ducts (vasa deferentia), which run posteriorly to copulatory apparatus. Sperm ducts not readily discernable in sections but must be very narrow. (Duct labelled “D” on fig. 5 of 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" pageId="18" pageNumber="885" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. 1998</bibRefCitation>
, is ovovitelline duct, not sperm duct.) Anterior to copulatory apparatus, each sperm duct expands to about 40 µm in diameter and forms a sperm storage structure (spermiducal vesicle) on either side. They then narrow (duct is occluded but visible over most of its length, but appears to be about 2.5 µm in diameter) and separately enter penis bulb. Penis with basal diameter about 170–200 µm and total (retracted) length about 450 µm. In both specimens, the distal end, about 150 µm, is reflected with diameter about 40 µm. Sperm ducts discharge separately but close together into anterior end of ejaculatory duct. Ejaculatory duct eccentric, in ventral half of penis, maximum diameter about 50 µm, lined with tall columnar cells, about 5 µm diameter in distal, reflected, portion.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5203512" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5203512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5203512/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="886" startId="19.[144,211,884,906]" targetBox="[144,1101,159,850]" targetPageId="19">
<paragraph blockId="19.[144,1101,884,1023]" pageId="19" pageNumber="886">
Figure 7. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mateos, Giribet and Carranza" authorityYear="1998" box="[246,414,884,906]" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Microplana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="19" pageNumber="886" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="nana">
<emphasis box="[246,414,884,906]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="886">Microplana nana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. (A) NHML 1998.2.9.1, sagittal section of the copulatory apparatus; anterior to the right. (B) NHML 1998.2.9.2, sagittal section of the copulatory apparatus; anterior to the right. (C) NHML 1998.2.9.1, sagittal reconstruction of the copulatory apparatus; anterior to the right. (D) NHML 1998.2.9.2, sagittal reconstruction of the copulatory apparatus; anterior to the right. Scale bars represent 200 µm in all figures.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="19.[144,1101,1090,1305]" pageId="19" pageNumber="886">
Ovaries, oviducts and vitellaria as described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" box="[747,985,1090,1114]" pageId="19" pageNumber="886" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. Oviducts extend posterior to penis and converge to separately join posterior extremity of female genital duct. Duct short, about 50 µm long and Y-shaped. Base of Y opens into posterior of atrium, each upper arm of the Y receiving one ovovitelline duct. Narrow genito-intestinal duct (
<figureCitation box="[401,498,1217,1241]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="19.[144,211,884,906]" captionTargetBox="[144,1101,159,850]" captionTargetId="figure-6@19.[144,1101,159,851]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 7. Microplana nana. (A) NHML 1998.2.9.1, sagittal section of the copulatory apparatus; anterior to the right. (B) NHML 1998.2.9.2, sagittal section of the copulatory apparatus; anterior to the right.(C) NHML 1998.2.9.1, sagittal reconstruction of the copulatory apparatus; anterior to the right. (D) NHML 1998.2.9.2, sagittal reconstruction of the copulatory apparatus; anterior to the right. Scale bars represent 200 µm in all figures." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5203512" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5203512/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="886">Figure 7</figureCitation>
) runs dorsally from female genital duct to branch of intestine. Many eosinophilic glands, presumably “shell gland” secreting the cocoon material, surround region around female genital duct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[144,261,1371,1394]" box="[144,261,1371,1394]" pageId="19" pageNumber="886">
<emphasis box="[144,261,1371,1394]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="886">Discussion</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[144,1101,1409,1688]" pageId="19" pageNumber="886">
The type material has been re-examined because details of the copulatory apparatus differ from the description and diagram given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" box="[750,973,1441,1465]" pageId="19" pageNumber="886" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. (1998</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 2) and accordingly the species is partially re-described above, as far as is necessary to correct the details.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[144,1101,1409,1688]" lastBlockId="20.[213,1170,166,254]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="887" pageId="19" pageNumber="886">
The differences between the description of 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" box="[682,914,1537,1561]" pageId="19" pageNumber="886" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
and the present description are as follows. First, the sperm ducts enter the penis separately and remain separate in the base of the penis until they discharge separately into the ejaculatory duct. They are shown in fig. 2 of 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" box="[516,741,1632,1656]" pageId="19" pageNumber="886" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
fusing before entering the penis bulb and discharging into the ejaculatory duct as a single duct. Second, the female genital duct is about 50 µm long, whereas it is shown as about 300 µm long in fig. 2 of 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" box="[244,473,198,222]" pageId="20" pageNumber="887" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. Third, there is a genito-intestinal duct running dorsally from the female genital duct. This was stated to be absent by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mateos E &amp; Giribet G &amp; Carranza S" box="[837,1064,230,254]" pageId="20" pageNumber="887" pagination="267 - 276" refId="ref11229" refString="Mateos E, Giribet G, Carranza S. 1998. Terrestrial planarians (Platyhelminthes, Terricola) from the Iberian Peninsula: first records of the family Rhynchodemidae, with the description of a new Microplana species. Contrib Zool. 67: 267 - 276." type="journal article" year="1998">Mateos et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
